<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-331-591  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 331 591.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Feb 6 1989 v15 n3 p54(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Does military Randamp;D stimulate commerce or the pork barrel? (researchand development)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Leibowitz, Michael R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Disagreement pervades among experts whether or not militaryresearch activities result in commercial spinoffs in privateindustry.andP;  Much of the military research budget is frequentlyjustified by defense officials as a source of commercialapplications.andP;  Some believe military research is equivalent togovernment funding for electronics research, much like theJapanese government supports its electronics industry.andP;  Militarycontractors and some competitors can find few examples ofcommercial successes achieved as a result of military research.andO;Some observers see the military effort as only a means of bloatingthe profits of some less than progressive electronics firms.andO;Historically, military research has provided the funding for anumber of technological advances in the computer industry.andP;  Therole of the military appears to be lessening as the private marketexpands.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MilitaryResearch and DevelopmentSpinoffsGovernment FundingIntegrated CircuitsElectronics.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>